␀␀␀J␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀L␀␀C␀␀␀(J␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀J␀␀␀␀␀J␀␀␀␀␀␀J␀␀␀␀␀␀J␀␀ ␀␀␀J␀␀␀␀␀K␀␀␀␀␀gL␀␀␀␀␀L␀␀T␀␀␀M␀␀;␀␀␀L␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀L␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀(J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀J␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀.G␀␀ ␀␀␀NG␀␀6␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀G␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀J␀␀␀␀␀␀,J␀␀q␀␀␀,J␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<html><title>Fixing Americas Strategic Airlift Problem</title><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center><h2>FIXING AMERICA'S STRATEGIC AIRLIFT PROBLEM</h2>By Thomas Moore<br>Deputy Director, Foreign Policy and Defense Studies<br><a href=/heritage>The Heritage Foundation</a><br>Backgrounder Update No. 263<br>November 1, 1995<br><p><hr width=50%></center><p>(Updating <i>A Safe and Prosperous America:  A U.S. Foreign and Defense Policy Blueprint</i>, The Heritage Foundation, 1994.)<p>This week the Pentagon's Defense Acquisition Board (DAB), which reviews and approves acquisition decisions in major defense programs, is meeting to consider options to preserve America's strategic airlift capability well into the next century. The DAB must decide whether to complete the full planned purchase of 120 McDonnell Douglas C-17s, the Air Force's newest heavy airlifter. If this option proves too expensive, the DAB must consider a mixed fleet of C-17s and other existing aircraft, including what the Air Force calls a Non-Developmental Airlift Aircraft, or NDAA.<p>The DAB is facing a momentous decision, since a robust strategic airlift capability is vital to the security of the United States. However, the cost of replacing America's current, aging strategic airlifters will be considerable. Supplementing the C-17 with the NDAA, a military version of Boeing's proven 747, may produce significant cost savings and still meet most of the Pentagon's future strategic lift requirements. <p><h3>THE IMPORTANCE OF STRATEGIC LIFT </h3><hr><p><b>America's Historic Strategy of "Forward Deployment"</b><p>In the 20th century the United States has been drawn into two global wars and numerous regional conflicts, but always with the luxury of fighting on someone else's soil, sparing the American homeland the ravages of war. This historical experience led the United States to adopt a strategic posture of "forward deployment" to contain the rise of Soviet Communism at the end of World War II. America's leaders determined to meet threats as far away from the continental United States as possible. For 45 years the U.S. has stationed large forces around the world, backed by the ability to reinforce and sustain those forces in the event of war. <p>However, the fall of the Soviet empire has brought about a dramatic withdrawal of forward deployed forces. American personnel in Europe have decreased from over half a million at the height of the Cold War to approximately 100,000 today. The growing integration of Europe and the rise of new security structures competing with NATO may bring that number down further in the future. The U.S. is turning over the Panama Canal to Panama and removing Southern Command forces from the Canal Zone. The U.S. has left the Philippines entirely, giving up naval and air bases that were the hub of the U.S. security posture in the Pacific. The Pentagon plans to maintain a force of 100,000 in the Pacific; but the future of the U.S. presence in Okinawa, recently wracked by demands for withdrawal, is in doubt. Even South Korea, a staunch ally which relies on Americans to help deter still-volatile North Korea, must contend with growing dissent over the U.S. presence. The clear pattern is one of global retrenchment and the inevitable return of most forward deployed forces to the United States.    <p><b>Protecting Vital Interests</b><p>Even though the United States is being compelled by budget cuts and other imperatives to pull back its far-flung forces, America's vital interests and obligations around the world are not undergoing a corresponding decline. The United States still has commitments or vital interests in Europe, the Middle East, throughout the Pacific region, and the Western Hemisphere. <p>The security and prosperity of the United States, a maritime trading power, depend as much as ever on unhindered passage of the world's sealanes and airspace, and on access to the world's raw materials and markets. America's leadership and credibility, essential elements of national security, depend on the ability to keep commitments to allies and friendly powers. <p><b>Replacing Forward Deployment with Force Projection</b><p>Without large, capable forces deployed close to the scene of potential conflicts, the United States may find it difficult to respond to a regional threat unless the nation replaces withdrawn forward deployed forces with the ability to project combat power to trouble spots. <P>Force projection includes the ability to deliver accurate attacks on key strategic targets like command, control, and communications centers or air defense networks early in a conflict. This is why America will continue to need the B-2 bomber, carrier-based naval strike forces to hit hard from the sea, and continued improvements in surveillance, real-time targeting, and precision-strike capabilities. <p>Force projection also means the ability to move men and equipment rapidly to the battlefield. Victory still depends, in the words of Confederate General Nathan Bedford Forrest, on "getting there first with the most."  Clearly the best way to get there first is by air. With enough heavy airlift, U.S. forces can arrive quickly with the weapons, munitions, spare parts, and heavy equipment needed to fight and prevail in a high-intensity campaign. <P>Of course, adequate sealift is required also to bring the huge stores needed to sustain the forces in a protracted conflict. But the Navy's fast sealift vessels require three weeks to reach the Persian Gulf, for example, and in warfare, time can be the decisive factor. Only strategic airlift can get troops and equipment into the theater in those critical early hours or days that can determine the outcome of the conflict. The U.S. can never rely on a future aggressor to give away the initiative as Saddam Hussein did in the Persian Gulf War, allowing the allies six months of unimpeded time in which to build up the force needed to throw him out of Kuwait. <p><b>America's Declining Strategic Airlift Capability</b><p>The Clinton Administration's Bottom-Up Review (BUR), which serves as the basis of current military strategy and force planning, calls for U.S. forces to be able to fight and win two nearly simultaneous medium regional conflicts. The BUR plan estimates that the strategic airlift requirement for such a scenario is 49-52 million ton miles per day (the measurement of tonnage carried over distance used by the Pentagon to compute its lift requirements). However, in the Persian Gulf War, the U.S. was able to deliver only about 17-21 million ton miles per day. That was an immense achievement. According to the U.S. military, it was equivalent to transporting the more than 500,000 residents of Seattle halfway around the world, along with all their cars, trucks, fuel, and food. But this level of airlift capacity may fall far short in the future if multiple, simultaneous crises erupt to threaten vital U.S. interests.<p>America's strategic airlift fleet, operated by the Air Mobility Command of the U.S. Air Force, is built around 231 heavy airlifters  the C-141 <i>Starlifter</i>, the C-5 <i>Galaxy</i>, the new C-17 <i>Globemaster</i> III, KC-10 and KC-135 tankers for aerial refueling, and a host of smaller support and command and control aircraft. KC-10 tankers also are being diverted for use as airlifters to meet shortfalls now common among the Command's C-141s. Supplementing the nation's strategic airlift fleet are 94 Guard and Reserve C-141s, C-5s, and tanker aircraft and the Civilian Reserve Air Fleet (CRAF), aircraft from civilian airlines brought into service in emergencies like Operation Desert Shield.<p>The problem is that this aging fleet is being used up at a faster rate than anticipated by the high number of sorties being flown in support of proliferating humanitarian and peace operations. No new C-5s nor C-141s are being built. The latest model C-141 entered service in 1979 and is nearing the end of its useful life, even after having gone through several overhauls or "SLEPs" (Service Life Extension Programs). These aircraft are simply wearing out and cannot fly much longer without endangering their crews. <p><b>OPTIONS TO REPLACE THE AGING FLEET</b><p>As the C-141 retires by FY 2003, the Pentagon proposes to replace the aging airlift fleet with the new McDonnell Douglas C-17, 40 of which will be authorized by the end of fiscal 1996 under current defense plans. At first the C-17 program was plagued with cost overruns, schedule delays, and performance shortfalls, but the company and the Air Force appear to have worked out most production problems. The C-17 program is now on the way to producing a truly outstanding airplane. It cannot carry as much cargo as the mammoth C-5, but it does accommodate outsize items like helicopters. It can land on short, rough, undeveloped airfields close to the battlefront (which used to be limited to the tactical C-130) and can maneuver in tight spots to unload quickly. It also can conduct airdrops of paratroops and heavy equipment. In July 1995 the C-17 underwent rigorous reliability, maintainability, and availability testing at Charleston, South Carolina, and passed the tests with the enthusiastic praise of the operators. <p>The Pentagon originally wanted to purchase 210 C-17s. The planned buy is now down to 120, and even though the unit cost is falling as the contractor perfects its manufacturing processes, the planned C-17 acquisition is still an expensive program. The Congressional Budget Office estimates the price per airplane at $251 million, including cost of support and spare parts. In total, the Pentagon would spend $21.2 billion to procure 80 more C-17s beyond the 40 expected to be approved in the fiscal 1996 defense bill. <p><b>CONVERTING EXISTING CIVILIAN AIRCRAFT FOR MILITARY AIRLIFT</b><P>The Defense Acquisition Board, in reviewing various solutions to the strategic airlift problem, must make a decision that will lead to one of the most significant aircraft procurements in U.S. history. The DAB must consider three main options:<p><ol><li>Complete the planned buy of 80 more C-17s;<p><li>Purchase fewer C-17s, order the restart of the closed production line of Lockheed Martin's C-5 <i>Galaxy</i>, and purchase more C-5s; and<p><li>Supplement a core C-17 fleet with a military version of the proven workhorse of the skies, the Boeing 747, which can be reconfigured for military use in a version known as the C-33.</ol><p>Since options two and three are cheaper, Congress is highly unlikely to approve option one, the full buy of 120 C-17s at a cost of $21.2 billion, if options two and three come close to fulfilling the ton-miles-per-day lift requirement. <p>While the C-5 is a capable aircraft with huge lift capacity, its advantages over the highly capable and more flexible C-17 do not appear sufficient to re-open production. On the other hand, the Boeing 747 freighter is in production now. This Non-Developmental Airlift Aircraft can easily be turned into an Air Force C-33 with reinforced cargo decks, a widened side cargo door, and a door in the nose for military cargo like trucks and wheeled artillery. <p>The C-33 cannot carry outsize cargo like helicopters or <i>Patriot</i> missile batteries. Those items can fly only on the C-5 or C-17. But the C-33 can carry as much cargo as the C-5, and considerably more palletized bulk cargo than the C-17. Moreover, the low-wing C-33 can fly faster and farther than the C-17 (7,000 nautical miles) without refueling. For example, a C-33 could haul 280,000 pounds of cargo from Maguire Air Force Base in New Jersey to Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, and then unload and fly back to a rear area base in Cairo before needing fuel.<p>The Air Force has done a study called the Strategic Airlift Force Mix Analysis, which looks at a variety of options for a mix of existing military aircraft like the C-5, the C-17, and the NDAA, supplemented by the Civilian Reserve Air Fleet. While it is up to the DAB and the technical and cost-effectiveness experts in the Pentagon to decide on the best mix, it is clear that a base force of C-17s combined with C-33s could meet almost all of the Air Force's ton-miles-per-day lift requirement, but at a considerable savings. <p>According to a newly released Congressional Budget Office memorandum ("Options for Strategic Airlift," October 1995), "If there was adequate room at airfields in regions of potential conflict, buying 32 more C-17's plus 30 C-33's would provide the same delivery capability as 80 additional C-17's. That option would also be nearly $8 billion cheaper...."<p>Seven or eight billion dollars in savings over the life of the program is considerable in light of today's defense budget pressures. Those savings could be applied to other vital national security programs like ballistic missile defense or the B-2 bomber without sacrificing essential strategic airlift requirements. In addition, using the military version of the Boeing 747 will produce savings in time as well as in money. It will speed up the availability of a highly capable airlifter to rebuild today's aging airlift fleet, which might not be up to the job in the event of another Desert Storm or multiple, simultaneous regional contingencies.<p>General Thomas Moorman, Jr., Vice Chief of Staff of the Air Force, says that "strategic lift has been the greatest deficiency in meeting the nation's two-conflict military strategy."  While supporting a robust C-17 program, the Defense Department and Congress have an historic opportunity to engage in meaningful acquisition reform by considering the C-33 to help fulfill the Pentagon's critical strategic lift requirement. At the same time, using the C-33 will rebuild the aging airlift fleet more quickly and produce significant savings in a period of tight defense budgets.<p><p><center><a href=/heritage/hbut.map><img src=/heritage/hbut.gif ismap border=0></a></center></body></html>  ␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀....()()))()()␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀>␀␀	␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀S␀u␀m␀m␀a␀r␀y␀I␀n␀f␀o␀r␀m␀a␀t␀i␀o␀n␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀(␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀P␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀@␀␀␀␀Y␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀@␀␀␀␀VK␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀@␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀Microsoft Word 6.0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀4␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀>␀␀	␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀0	␀␀n	␀␀?␀␀d␀␀Q␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀#␀␀-␀␀?␀␀N␀␀Y+␀␀c+␀␀?/␀␀J/␀␀9␀␀9␀␀9␀␀9␀␀:␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀