<DOCOLDNO>IA073-000479-B024-5</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.conservative.org:80/lead-inst/morton/support.html 204.71.237.88 19970208232955 text/html 5202
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 08-Feb-97 23:30:39 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 03-Oct-96 13:23:20 GMT
Content-length: 5015
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>"Liberals" fund Institute programs</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<H2>Probe shows alumni of leftist academic bastions 
donate in droves to the Leadership Institute
</H2></center>
<P>
<BR>
<B>	BY BRETT BUICK</B>
<P>
	Believe it or not.
<BR>
<DD>	A Building Leadership special investigation reveals that elements of the liberal establishment are secretly financing the Leadership Institute.<BR>
<DD>	A mystified Morton Blackwell, president of the Leadership Institute, initially expressed shock at the disclosure. "I don't understand it," he said.  "I've been fighting liberals for years.  It's hard to believe they've been supporting the Institute."
<DD>	Kevin Gentry, executive vice president of the Leadership Institute, was characteristically more terse: "Impossible."
<DD>	But an analysis of responses to a recent survey of Leadership Institute supporters reveals that many of them attended infamous bastions of trendy academic leftism like Harvard, Yale, the University of Michigan and Dartmouth.
<DD>	The establishment influence is so strong that the <a href= "alum.html"> Leadership Institute ranking </a> parallels the well-known U.S. News and World Report ranking of America's top 25 universities.
<DD>	One of the biggest surprises of the survey is that Harvard and Yale  topped the charts as alma maters of respondents, with twenty-five each.  The University of Michigan (21) was next.  Purdue (16), MIT (15), Stanford (15)  and Cornell (14) rounded out the top seven.  
<DD>	Such results prompt the question of how so many Institute donorsactually conservative, not liberalmanaged to survive the pervasive liberal atmosphere of their campuses.   
<DD>	Columnist William F. Buckley, who attended Yale University, once said he would rather be governed by the first one thousand names of the Boston phone book than by the faculty of Harvard.  If Buckley knew Harvard and Yale topped the charts in producing Leadership Institute supporters, he'd probably be as stunned as Morton.
<DD>	William Page, an Institute supporter and Harvard alumnus, sees academics' lack of hands on, real-world experience as a reason for their liberalism.  "Much time is wasted by people talking who haven't been in the trenches," he said.
<DD>	Other Institute supporters suggest pervasive liberalism at well-known campuses is a relatively recent phenomenon, and that eastern establishment schools weren't as liberal in the past.
<DD>	One long-time Institute supporter, Edward L. Adams, sees the sixties as the cause of the schools' liberal lurch.  He observed, "My alma mater, the University of Michigan, gave away all kinds of things to radicals."  However, Adams does see hope: "Through the work of the Leadership Institute, liberal schools may be coming back [toward conservative philosophy]."
<DD>	Another possible explanation for the conservative remnant is that many Leadership Institute supporters attended college during and after the World War II period, in a more serious academic environment.  Purdue graduate and Institute supporter Daniel Worth said, "Being at college during the war left us with no time to worry about political correctness."
<DD>	One reassuring result of the surveys is that liberal strongholds weren't the only institutions to educate Leadership Institute supporters.  The U.S. Naval Academy at Annapolis (11) and the U.S. Military Academy at West Point (10) both made the top 20.  
<DD>	The Midwest heartland made a very strong showing, with the universities of Illinois (13), Minnesota (12) and Northwestern (12) joining Purdue and Michigan.
<DD>	While the East Coast and Midwest dominated the list, the West Coast was also represented, by Stanford, the University of Southern California (13) and UCLA (10).
<DD>	The South was underrepresented, with only the University of Texas (9) making the cut, but the region still demonstrated its strength, with several schools falling just short of the list.
<DD>	As the South rises again in the next century, however, the top rankings may change.In all, there were 317 alma maters listed.  Supporters returned  839 surveys.
Institute supporters were divided on whether today's youth should attend traditional leading institutions or turn to rising conservative schools like Hillsdale College.
<DD>	However, the supporters would probably all agree with Mr. Page: "Wherever you go, watch out for people with short left legs."
<P>
<BR>
	<B>If you missed the Leadership Institute supporter survey but still wish to complete it, please contact Ric Andersen at (800)827-5323 or (703)247-2000.</B>
<P>
